              "id": "glog-32cca92b-058a-4932-9ec1-6ac497ffe3c8",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Security Concern: Detected Use of subprocess call with shell=True\" in Python arises when the `subprocess.call()` function is used with the `shell=True` argument. This can lead to security risks such as shell injection, where an attacker can execute arbitrary commands on the system. This is particularly dangerous if the input to the command is not properly sanitized, as it can allow an attacker to execute malicious commands.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using `shell=True` unless absolutely necessary. Instead, pass the command and its arguments as a list. This prevents shell injection by not invoking the shell directly.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the vulnerable code:\n\n```python\nimport glob\nimport os\n\n# Get a list of all .csv files\ncsv_files = glob.glob('*.csv')\n\n# Remove each .csv file\nfor file in csv_files:\n    os.remove(file)\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard Python libraries:\n\n- `glob`\n- `os`\n\nThese libraries are part of the Python Standard Library and do not require additional installation.\n\n### Relevant Resources\n\n- [OWASP Command Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Command_Injection)\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "B602"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "glog-0d09b956-c96a-4e83-903b-f09f8cc764c9",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe vulnerability arises from the use of the `eval()` function in Python, which can execute arbitrary code. This can lead to security risks if the input to `eval()` is not properly sanitized, as it may allow an attacker to execute malicious code. In this specific case, the code `size = eval('size'+' '+ iterator)` is vulnerable because it evaluates a string that could be manipulated to include harmful code.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using `eval()` whenever possible. Instead, use safer alternatives such as `ast.literal_eval()` when you need to evaluate a string containing a Python literal or expression. `ast.literal_eval()` is safer because it only evaluates strings containing literals and expressions, not arbitrary code.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `eval()` with `ast.literal_eval()` if the input is expected to be a Python literal. If the input is not a literal, consider other ways to safely parse or handle the input.\n\n```python\nimport ast\n\n# Assuming 'iterator' is a string that represents a literal\nsize = ast.literal_eval('size' + ' ' + iterator)\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard library:\n\n- `ast`: This is a built-in Python library, so no additional installation is required.\n\n### Relevant OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "B307"
                ]
              }
            },
